  "output": "## Findings\n\nThis is a Python async scraper pipeline (fetchers → filter → SQLite dedup → notify), not a web app — there's no React/JS anywhere in the repo, so re-render analysis doesn't apply. I mapped the requested categories onto what's actually here: SQLite access patterns, async HTTP pagination, regex/hash recomputation, and long-term storage growth.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job, `diff()` does one `SELECT` then one `INSERT`/`UPDATE`, all inside a Python loop — 2N round trips to SQLite per run. With `sources.yaml` covering 100+ boards, a single run can push thousands of `Job` rows through this one at a time.\n\n```python\n# current: N SELECTs + N INSERT/UPDATEs, one connection round trip each\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nFix: batch-load existing hashes with one `IN (...)` query (chunked for SQLite's variable limit), then `executemany` for inserts/updates:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    existing = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):          # SQLite var-count limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i+500]\n        qmarks = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in\n            cur.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qmarks})\", chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, inserts, updates, touches = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touches.append({\"now\": now, \"key\": job.key})\n\n    if inserts: cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ... :now, :now)\", inserts)\n    if updates: cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", updates)\n    if touches: cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\", touches)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nCollapses ~2N queries to O(N/500 + 3).\n\n### 2. The real \"N+1\" here: serialized pagination in async fetchers\n\nThis is the biggest win in the codebase. `fetch_workday`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_apple`, `fetch_optiver`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_bytedance`, `fetch_eightfold` all paginate with a plain `for`/`while` loop and `await` each page sequentially — e.g. `fetchers.py:651-699` (Workday, `page_size=20`, cap `offset>5000` → up to 250 sequential HTTP round trips per tenant), `fetchers.py:947-967` (Amazon, `max_pages=40`). `sources.yaml` configures 4 Workday tenants and all the big-tech bespoke boards this way — despite `concurrency: 8` letting *different sources* run in parallel, pagination *within* a source is fully serial network latency, not CPU.\n\n```python\n# current (fetchers.py:674-698, representative of ~9 fetchers)\nwhile True:\n    data = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json=body, ...)\n    ...\n    offset += page_size\n    if not postings or offset >= total or offset > 5000:\n        break\n```\n\nFix: fetch page 1 to learn `total`, then fire the rest concurrently under a small semaphore instead of one-at-a-time:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_workday(client, source):\n    ...\n    first = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={**body_base, \"offset\": 0}, ...)\n    postings = list(first.get(\"jobPostings\", []))\n    total = min(first.get(\"total\", len(postings)), 5000)\n\n    sem = asyncio.Semaphore(5)\n    async def page(offset):\n        async with sem:\n            data = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\",\n                                   json={**body_base, \"offset\": offset}, ...)\n            return data.get(\"jobPostings\", [])\n\n    offsets = range(page_size, total, page_size)\n    for batch in await asyncio.gather(*(page(o) for o in offsets)):\n        postings.extend(batch)\n    ...\n```\n\nFor the fetchers that stop early on an empty/stale page (Google, Apple, Amazon, etc.), do this in bounded batches (e.g. 5 pages at a time) and stop launching new batches once a batch comes back with no fresh IDs — preserves the early-exit behavior while parallelizing within each batch.\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — regex recompilation per job, `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`_compile(include)` / `_compile(exclude)` run inside `match()`, which is called once per job in `filter_jobs`'s list comprehension (`filters.py:49`). With ~14 keywords in `sources.yaml`, that's 14 `re.escape` + `re.compile` calls *per job*, every run, instead of once per pipeline run.\n\n```python\n# current: recompiled for every job\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled here\n```\n\nFix — compile once, outside the per-job loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] = (), exclude: list[re.Pattern] = (), cutoff=None):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude): return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include): return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 4. Minor redundant computation — `content_hash` hashed twice per job, `store.py:67-69` + `models.py:66-69`\n\n`content_hash` is a `@property` (SHA-256 over a joined string), recomputed on every access. `diff()` reads it once for the comparison (`store.py:67`), then `_insert`/`_update` call `job.to_row()` which reads `self.content_hash` again (`models.py:75`) — two hashes per job. Cheap in isolation (~microseconds), but free to fix once you're already touching `diff()` for the batching change above: compute it once and pass it through instead of re-deriving.\n\n### 5. Caching opportunity — no conditional HTTP requests\n\nEvery scheduled run (12h cadence per recent commits) fully re-fetches every board from scratch — there's no ETag/If-Modified-Since handling in `_request` (`fetchers.py:31-47`), even though most listings are unchanged between runs. Greenhouse/Ashby/Lever APIs generally don't support conditional GET well, but for the paginated bespoke fetchers you could at least short-circuit: if page 1's job-ID set is identical to what's stored for that source in `meta`, skip deeper pagination entirely. Given finding #2 already cuts most of the latency, this is a secondary win — worth it mainly for sources with very large boards (Amazon, Microsoft) where most 12h-cycles produce zero new postings.\n\n### 6. Storage growth (\"memory leak\" analog) — `jobs.db` never prunes closed postings\n\nEach process run exits after `pipeline.run()` completes (`pipeline.py:52`), so classic in-process memory leaks (growing caches, unclosed listeners) don't really apply here — there's no long-running daemon. The actual unbounded-growth risk is in persistent storage: `Store.diff()` only inserts/updates, it never removes rows for postings that disappeared from a board (filled/withdrawn reqs). `jobs.db` (currently 385KB) will grow forever across 12h runs × 100+ sources, and every `SELECT` in `diff()`/`added_since()` pays the cost of an ever-larger table with no reclamation.\n\nFix — track which keys were seen this run per source and mark/delete the rest:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs, *, source_company: str | None = None):\n    ...\n    if source_company is not None:\n        seen_keys = {j.key for j in jobs}\n        cur.execute(\"DELETE FROM jobs WHERE company = ? AND key NOT IN ({})\"\n                    .format(\",\".join(\"?\" * len(seen_keys))),\n                    [source_company, *seen_keys])\n```\n\nor simpler: a periodic `DELETE FROM jobs WHERE last_seen < ?` (e.g. drop anything not seen in 30 days), run once at the end of a full pipeline pass, plus an occasional `VACUUM`.\n\n### Priority order\n1. Parallelize pagination in the bespoke fetchers (#2) — largest wall-clock win, affects every scheduled run.\n2. Batch `Store.diff()` (#1) — straightforward, removes thousands of round trips.\n3. Hoist regex compilation out of the per-job filter loop (#3) — trivial, no behavior change.\n4. Add row pruning to `jobs.db` (#6) — prevents unbounded growth over months of 12h runs.\n5. Conditional-request/skip-on-unchanged caching (#5) and dedup the double hash (#4) — nice-to-haves, lower impact.\n",
